LUDWIG MIES VAN DER ROHE
1886-1969 → 2021

[CAT] Tal dia com avui de 1969, l'arquitecte Mies van der Rohe va morir a Chicago, Illinois. 52 anys després, continuem admirant la seva obra i promovent el coneixement del seu #llegat.
Més informació sobre la seva història a: www.miesbcn.com

[ENG] On a day like today in 1969, architect Mies van der Rohe died in Chicago, Illinois.
52 years later, we continue admiring his work and promoting the knowledge of his #legacy.
Find out more about his story at: www.miesbcn.com

[ESP] Tal día como hoy de 1969, el arquitecto Mies van der Rohe murió en Chicago, Illinois. 52 años después, seguimos admirando su obra y promoviendo el conocimiento de su #legado.
Más información e historia: www.miesbcn.com

🎥⬇️

node.text:
Meeting room for great Company @mgid.ua
style_Loft
Area_42 m2
designed in Kyiv
www.solmazprimavera.com
A handmade sculpture soars in the air. This is the logo of the company ... or rather its birth. The idea was that the logo was in the process of being created; the sculptor was hollowing it out from a stone fragment of a rock.
Architect @solmaz_primavera_architect (Solmaz Fooladi) did not close the ventilation on the ceiling, but only beat it in the interior, keeping the height of the ceiling. The meeting room is light and spacious, new ideas and solutions have a place to roam.
This project was a design gamble. Drop of concrete and sculpture existed only on paper, the project was approved, there is no turning back. Ahead was the difficult task of translating fantasy into reality. But for the author there are no obstacles in order to carry out his plans. The sculpture was altered several times, but it did not correspond to the sketch at all. The author herself intervened in the creation process and literally brought it to perfection with his own hands.
Above the table is a light fixture. It consists of seventy pyramids of various thicknesses and sizes. The designer associates them with a flock of birds flying towards the portal, which is the entrance door. Doors of orange, bright color are made against a background of dark glass. Textiles have been added to the interior: curtains, armchair upholstery, a bright orange armchair to match the front door. Fresh flowers are also present. All this gives life to this project.

node.text:
Drift Bridge / Volkan Alkanoglu
Photographs: 
Peter Molick, Jennifer Boomer
.
Drift, a timber-and-steel pedestrian bridge by designer Volkan Alkanoglu, has been completed and will be installed in Fort Worth, TX in Summer 2021. Fabricated off-site with a projected installation time of just a few hours, Drift is an innovative example of plug-and-play urbanism, an emerging sustainable and affordable design strategy that proposes building infrastructural elements off-site and dropping them into place.

Via @gadfoundation

node.text:
This railing in Naples has Braille to describe the view. What do you think?

Sitting atop a hill that overlooks the Italian city of Naples is the Castel Sant'Elmo (St Elmo Castle) which is a popular tourist haunt. Hundreds walk up to the top of the castle to enjoy the view but there is yet another attraction on display in the castle. A 92-foot-long piece of stainless steel is attached to the wall fence of the castle of one of its large sized windows and it has a poetic description of the view in Braille.

The unique railing was installed by artist Paolo Puddu in 2015 and titled 'Follow the Shape' and has been a permanent fixture at the castle since 2017, a report on Ozy.com said. The art had won the fifth edition of the 'A Work For the Castle' contest.

Visitors are encouraged to feel the installation wherein they run their hands on the rail and those who can read the Braille script can 'follow the shape' on the railing to read the verses from Italian author Giuseppe de Lorenzo's 'La terra e l'uomo' or the 'The Land and the Man'.

The inscription is carved in both Italian and English and tourists are asked to imagine the stunning view in front of them. The view is of the Tyrrhenian Sea and Italy's Mount Vesuvius.
Credit - @engineeringandarchitecture

All credit belongs to the owner.

Via @desiindianarchitect
